# React Patterns

## Components

- Function components only. No class components.
- One component per file. File name matches component name (`FansPanel.tsx` → `FansPanel`).
- Type props explicitly with an exported `interface FooProps`. Don't inline anonymous prop types.
- Prefer children composition over "god" components with many boolean flags.

```tsx
interface PanelProps {
	title: string;
	children: React.ReactNode;
}

export default function Panel({ title, children }: PanelProps) {
	return (
		<section>
			<h2>{title}</h2>
			{children}
		</section>
	);
}
```

## State & Effects

- Derive, don't duplicate. If a value can be computed from props/state, compute it — don't store it.
- Effects are for syncing with external systems (fetch, subscriptions). Don't use `useEffect` to transform state in response to other state.
- Always specify the full dependency array. Don't silence `react-hooks/exhaustive-deps`.
- Extract non-trivial side-effect logic into a custom hook (`useFans`, `useGhosts`, …) and keep the component declarative.

## Data Fetching

- Call the `src/api/instagramServer.ts` helpers — never `fetch` inline in a component.
- Render three states explicitly: loading, error, success. Don't render stale data next to an error.

```tsx
if (loading) return <Spinner />;
if (error) return <ErrorBanner message={error.message} />;
return <List items={data} />;
```

## Context

- `UserContext` is the single source of truth for the selected Instagram user. Don't pass `user` through props when the context is available.
- Keep contexts small and focused. Split before they grow multi-purpose.

## JSX Hygiene

- Use semantic elements (`<button>`, `<nav>`, `<section>`) over `<div>` with `role`.
- Give every list item a stable `key` — never the array index for reorderable lists.
- Self-close empty elements: `<NavBar />`, not `<NavBar></NavBar>`.

## Styling

- CSS lives in `src/styles/`, imported from the component that owns it.
- Use BEM-ish class names already present in the codebase (`panel`, `panel__title`, etc.) — don't introduce a CSS framework without discussion.
